<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="growth-onboarding-emails">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>content-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Behavior-triggered email sequences for user activation: one CTA per email, fires on user action/inaction, escalation ladder for stuck users. Outperforms time-based by 15-40%.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>onboarding</tag>
      <tag>behavioral-triggers</tag>
      <tag>activation</tag>
      <tag>user-retention</tag>
      <tag>email-sequences</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Onboarding Email Sequences</title>
    <summary>Behavior-triggered email sequences that guide new users from signup to activation. Each email has one CTA, fires on a specific user action (or inaction), and routes stuck users through an escalation ladder. Behavioral triggers outperform time-based sequences by 15-40% in activation rate.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Users who sign up and see no tailored follow-up abandon before reaching the "aha moment." Behavior-driven sequences intercept users at the exact moment they stall, deliver contextual nudges, and route high-value users to human outreach — all without manual effort.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>SaaS or app with free trial / freemium model and measurable activation steps</item>
        <item>Onboarding activation rate below 50% with no behavioral trigger emails in place</item>
        <item>Redesigning an existing time-based sequence to add behavior-triggered branches</item>
        <item>New product launch where the first-week user journey has been mapped</item>
        <item>Product has an identifiable "aha moment" milestone (connect data, create project, invite teammate)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Product analytics not set up — behavioral triggers require event tracking (Segment, Mixpanel); without data, only time-based sequences are possible</item>
        <item>Transactional product with no recurring engagement cycle (one-time purchase, no return)</item>
        <item>User base is extremely homogeneous with a single known path — a 3-email linear sequence may outperform complex branching</item>
        <item>No ESP with automation capability — Customer.io, ActiveCampaign, or Intercom required; basic Mailchimp is insufficient</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="user-segmentation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Segment users before writing any email — each segment receives a different path with different goals.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic sequences treat activated users and inactive users identically, wasting effort and triggering unsubscribes from engaged users.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>New + Active: engaged, hitting milestones → accelerate to activation</item>
        <item>New + Stuck: started but stopped → remove blockers</item>
        <item>New + Inactive: signed up, no activity → re-engage</item>
        <item>Activated: hit aha moment → path to conversion</item>
        <item>At-risk: dropping engagement → win back</item>
      </list>
      <p>Segment dimensions: signup source, use case, company size, actual behavior.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="trigger-types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use behavior-triggered emails as the primary mechanism; supplement with time-based emails only for users with no trackable actions.</statement>
        <rationale>Behavioral triggers outperform time-based sequences by 15-40% in activation rate because they reach users at the exact moment of need.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Time trigger: days since signup (e.g., Day 3 feature highlight)</item>
        <item>Action trigger: user completed step X (e.g., "You created a project!")</item>
        <item>Inaction trigger: step X NOT completed within Y days (e.g., "Did you get stuck?")</item>
        <item>Hybrid: time + behavior condition (e.g., Day 3 AND not activated)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="core-8-email-sequence">
      <rule>
        <statement>Map each email to a single trigger event and a single goal before writing copy.</statement>
        <rationale>Emails with mixed goals produce mixed results; the sequence design determines effectiveness more than individual copy quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>1. Signup → Welcome: set expectations, prompt first action</item>
        <item>2. Didn't complete action → Gentle nudge: remove blocker</item>
        <item>3. Completed first action → Celebration + next step: build momentum</item>
        <item>4. Day 3 if not activated → Feature education: show value</item>
        <item>5. Completed activation → Path to power use: deepen engagement</item>
        <item>6. Day 7 trial → Mid-point check: offer help</item>
        <item>7. High usage → Social proof + upgrade: convert</item>
        <item>8. Low usage → Re-engagement: rescue</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="escalation-ladder">
      <rule>
        <statement>Build a 6-level escalation path for users who take no action after signup; cap escalation frequency at 1 email per day maximum.</statement>
        <rationale>Without escalation, stuck users silently churn. Without a frequency cap, users unsubscribe — hurting overall deliverability.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Level 1 — No action, Day 2: helpful email</item>
        <item>Level 2 — No action, Day 5: different angle email</item>
        <item>Level 3 — No action, Day 7: video tutorial link</item>
        <item>Level 4 — No action, Day 10: personal outreach offer</item>
        <item>Level 5 — No action, Day 12: extension or special offer</item>
        <item>Level 6 — Trial ends: exit survey</item>
      </list>
      <note>The Day 10 personal outreach email scales to approximately 200 new signups/month without a dedicated success team. Above that threshold, route to a Slack notification for a human to review rather than fully automated send.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="email-structure-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Each onboarding email must contain exactly one CTA — one button or one link, never both.</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple CTAs split attention and reduce completion. The single-action constraint forces clarity about the email's purpose.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Write body copy at 3-5 sentences maximum in short paragraphs (1-2 sentences each).</statement>
        <rationale>Onboarding emails compete with product notifications; walls of text get skipped. Short paragraphs signal respect for user time.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Write from a named person (founder or CS rep), not from a company account, during the onboarding phase.</statement>
        <rationale>Personal tone outperforms branded templates in onboarding; plain text often outperforms HTML for the first 14 days.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Subject: 4-7 words, get opened</item>
        <item>Preview text: 40-60 chars, enhances open rate</item>
        <item>Opening: 1-2 sentences, personal connection</item>
        <item>Body: 3-5 sentences, single message</item>
        <item>CTA: one action, button or link (not both)</item>
        <item>PS: optional secondary info (reply invitation works well here)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="performance-targets">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track email-received-to-action-completed conversion per email, not just open or click rate.</statement>
        <rationale>Open and click metrics measure email quality; the activation conversion metric measures whether the email achieves its actual goal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Open rate target: 50%+ (below → fix subject line)</item>
        <item>Click rate target: 10%+ (below → fix CTA or copy)</item>
        <item>Conversion target: 5%+ (below → reduce friction in product)</item>
        <item>Unsubscribe cap: &lt;0.5% (above → check frequency)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ab-testing-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>A/B test subject lines in the first 4 hours post-send; do not run subject line tests on emails older than 24 hours.</statement>
        <rationale>Onboarding email recency is critical — stale tests are not representative of how current subscribers respond to the trigger context.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="esp-integration-notes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Specify the ESP (Customer.io, ConvertKit, ActiveCampaign) in every agent prompt producing email copy — personalization token syntax varies by platform.</statement>
        <rationale>Customer.io uses {{customer.first_name}}; ConvertKit uses {{subscriber.first_name}}. Wrong tokens produce broken personalization silently.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <note>Trigger conditions described in natural language must be translated into ESP-specific automation logic by a human — never deploy agent-described conditions directly to an ESP without human configuration.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="common-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending more than one email per day during onboarding.</description>
        <reason>Frequency above 1/day causes unsubscribe spikes that hurt overall deliverability, not just the onboarding sequence. Deliverability damage is disproportionate to the marginal activation gain.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Including multiple CTAs in a single onboarding email (e.g., "Complete setup" AND "Explore features" AND "Invite a teammate").</description>
        <reason>Multiple CTAs split user attention. The user chooses nothing or the wrong thing. One email, one action.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using only time-based triggers (Day 1, Day 3, Day 7) with no behavioral conditions.</description>
        <reason>Time-based emails reach activated and inactive users identically. An activated user receives a "still getting started?" email after completing setup — undermining trust.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using generic copy not tied to segment or trigger context (e.g., "Here are some tips!" to all users regardless of their activity).</description>
        <reason>Generic copy signals the email was not written for the recipient. Personalization based on actual behavior (even "I see you created a project") doubles reply rate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping the escalation path — no emails for users who take no action after Day 2.</description>
        <reason>Users who get stuck silently churn. Without escalation, the sequence abandons users at the exact moment they need help most.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using personalization tokens without verifying the ESP's event tracking is reliably firing them (e.g., "You created your first project!" when the event is not reliably tracked).</description>
        <reason>Broken personalization is worse than no personalization — it signals a broken product or broken communication system.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Automating the Day 10 personal outreach email at full scale without a human review step.</description>
        <reason>Personal outreach emails feel authentic only if they can be followed up. A fully automated "book a call" email with no human behind it damages trust when the user tries to reply.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/email-welcome.txt" purpose="Welcome email — first action, reply-friendly tone"/>
      <template path="templates/email-nudge.txt" purpose="Stuck-user nudge — blocker removal, Day 2 trigger"/>
      <template path="templates/email-celebration.txt" purpose="Completion celebration — milestone + next step"/>
      <template path="templates/email-personal-outreach.txt" purpose="High-value signup — personal call offer, Day 10"/>
      <template path="templates/email-trial-end.txt" purpose="Trial ending — activated user conversion push"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-sequence-design.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to design full trigger logic table"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-email-draft.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to draft one email per trigger event"/>
    </templates>
